Cut, Copy and Paste in VimIn this quick Vim tip, learn about cutting and copying-pasting. https://itsfoss.com/vim-cut-copy-paste/ 653259748ebe181c27ab4f34 VimSagar Sharma Thu, 26 Oct 2023 03:35:30 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cut-copy-paste-in-vim.png" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim"><p>剪切、复制和粘贴文本是文本编辑中最基本的任务之一，我们都知道 Vim 有不同的处理方式。</p><p>这意味着，在你掌握它之前，你会害怕它，一旦你掌握了它，它就只是一个兔子洞。</p><p>虽然我将详细介绍剪切、复制和粘贴，但这里是本教程的基本摘要，以帮助您开始使用：</p><table><thead><tr><th><strong>行动</strong></th><th><strong>描述</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>yiw</code></td><td>复制当前单词。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>yy</code></td><td>复制整行。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>diw</code></td><td>剪切当前单词。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>dd</code></td><td>剪掉整条线。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>p</code></td><td>粘贴文本。</td></tr></tbody></table><p>别担心，Vim 为您提供的选项比我上面提到的要多得多。</p><p>在本教程中，我将引导您完成以下内容：</p><ul><li>如何在 Vim 中复制文本</li><li>如何在 Vim 中剪切文本</li><li>如何在 Vim 中粘贴文本</li><li>如何使用可视模式在 Vim 中剪切和复制文本</li></ul><p>那么让我们从第一个开始。</p><h2 id="how-to-copy-the-text-in-the-vim-editor">如何在 Vim 编辑器中复制文本</h2><p>虽然我们使用术语“复制”，但 Vim 有一个不同的术语，称为<code>yank</code> ，因此从现在开始，我将使用“Yank”而不是“复制”。</p><p>正如我之前提到的，您可以使用多种方法在 Vim 中提取文本，以下是一些有用的方法：</p><table><thead><tr><th>命令</th><th>描述</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>nyy</code>或<code>nY</code></td><td>复制（复制）当前行和接下来的<code>n-1</code>行。例如， <code>3yy</code>复制当前行及其下面的两行。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>yaw</code></td><td>猛拉（复制）光标所在的当前单词。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>yy</code>或<code>Y</code></td><td>猛拉（复制）整个当前行。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>y$</code></td><td>将文本从光标复制到行尾。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>y^</code>或<code>y0</code></td><td>将文本从光标复制到行首。</td></tr></tbody></table><p>要在 Vim 中进行拉取，请执行以下 3 个简单步骤：</p><ol><li>按<code>Esc</code>键切换到普通模式</li><li>导航到要复制的行或单词</li><li>按上表中的相关命令，您的文本将被复制</li></ol><p>想学习交互式复制台词的方式吗？跳到本教程的最后一部分。</p><h2 id="how-to-cut-text-in-the-vim-editor">如何在 Vim 编辑器中剪切文本</h2><p>在 Vim 中，您没有任何删除文本的选项。相反，您剪切文本，因此删除和剪切文本与 Vim 中的操作类似。</p><p>要在 Vim 中剪切文本，请按<code>d</code>命令。但你永远不会在没有任何意见的情况下使用<code>d</code>命令。你总是会添加一些东西来从中获得更多。</p><p>以下是一些使用<code>d</code>命令剪切文本的实用方法：</p><table><thead><tr><th>命令</th><th>描述</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>dd</code></td><td>剪切整个当前行。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>d$</code></td><td>将文本从光标剪切到行尾。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>d^</code>或<code>d0</code></td><td>将文本从光标剪切到行首。</td></tr><tr><td> <code>ndd</code>或<code>dN</code></td><td> Cuts the current line and the next <code>n-1</code> lines. For example, <code>3dd</code> cuts the current line and the two lines below it.</td></tr><tr><td> <code>daw</code></td><td> Cuts the current word the cursor is on.</td></tr></tbody></table><p> Let&#39;s say I want to cut the first 4 lines from my file, then I need to use <code>4dd</code> and here&#39;s how I did it: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cut-multiple-lines-in-the-Vim-editor.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim" loading="lazy" width="743" height="370" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Cut-multiple-lines-in-the-Vim-editor.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cut-multiple-lines-in-the-Vim-editor.gif 743w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="how-to-paste-text-in-the-vim-editor"> How to paste text in the Vim editor</h2><p> After copying or cutting text in Vim, you can simply paste it by pressing the <code>p</code> key.</p><p> You can press the <code>p</code> key multiple times to paste text multiple times or use <code>np</code> where the <code>n</code> is the number of how many times you want to paste the text.</p><p> For example, here, I pasted lines that I copied previously three times: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/paste-lines-in-Vim-editor.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim" loading="lazy" width="743" height="370" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/paste-lines-in-Vim-editor.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/paste-lines-in-Vim-editor.gif 743w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> It&#39;s that easy!</p><h2 id="how-to-cut-and-copy-text-by-selecting-it"> How to cut and copy text by selecting it</h2><p> If you are coming from GUI text editors, you must be used to copying and cutting text by selecting it.</p><p> So let&#39;s start with how you copy text by selecting it in Vim.</p><h3 id="copy-the-text-by-selecting-it"> Copy the text by selecting it</h3><p> To copy the text in visual mode, follow 3 simple steps:</p><ol><li> Go to the point from where you want to start the selection</li><li> Press <code>Ctrl + v</code> to enable the visual mode</li><li> Use arrow keys to make a selection</li><li> Press the <code>y</code> key to copy the selected text</li></ol><p> For example, here, I copied 4 lines using the visual mode: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Copy-lines-in-vim-by-selecting-them.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim" loading="lazy" width="743" height="370" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Copy-lines-in-vim-by-selecting-them.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Copy-lines-in-vim-by-selecting-them.gif 743w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> If you notice, once I pressed the <code>y</code> key, it showed how many lines were yanked (copied). In my case, 4 lines were yanked.</p><h3 id="cut-the-text-by-selecting-it-in-vim"> Cut the text by selecting it in Vim</h3><p> To cut the text in Vim in visual mode, all you have to do is follow 4 simple steps:</p><ol><li> Navigate to a point from where you want to cut lines</li><li> Press <code>Ctrl + v</code> to switch to visual mode</li><li> Use arrow keys to select the lines you want to cut</li><li> Press the <code>d</code> key to cut the selected lines</li></ol><p> So let&#39;s say I want to cut 4 lines, then, this is how I&#39;d do it: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cut-lines-in-Vim-by-selecting-them.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim" loading="lazy" width="743" height="370" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Cut-lines-in-Vim-by-selecting-them.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cut-lines-in-Vim-by-selecting-them.gif 743w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Pretty easy. Right?</p><h2 id="more-on-vim"> More on Vim</h2><p> Did you know that there are multiple modes in Vim? <a href="https://linuxhandbook.com/vim-modes/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Learn more about different modes in Vim:</a></p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://linuxhandbook.com/vim-modes/?ref=itsfoss.com"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">What are Vim Modes? How to Change Them?</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Vim has three different modes for handling user input and processing them.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://linuxhandbook.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2021/08/Linux-Handbook-New-Logo.png" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">Linux Handbook</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Team LHB</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://linuxhandbook.com/content/images/2022/04/vim-modes.png" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim"></div></a></figure><p> Want to step up your Vim game? Refer to <a href="https://linuxhandbook.com/pro-vim-tips/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">tips and tricks to become a pro-Vim user</a> :</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://linuxhandbook.com/pro-vim-tips/?ref=itsfoss.com"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">11 Pro Vim Tips to Get Better Editing Experience</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">You can learn plenty of Vim tips on your own, or you can learn it from others&#39; experiences.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://linuxhandbook.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2021/08/Linux-Handbook-New-Logo.png" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">Linux Handbook</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Pratham Patel</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://linuxhandbook.com/content/images/2022/08/pro-vim-tips.png" alt="Cut, Copy and Paste in Vim"></div></a></figure><p> I hope you will find this guide helpful.</p> ; 
Install, Configure and Use Remmina on UbuntuHere's how to use Remmina on Ubuntu to connect to Linux or Windows remote systems. https://itsfoss.com/use-remmina/ 652776dc030e5e08c7c31912 TutorialUbuntuAnkush Das Tue, 24 Oct 2023 03:48:09 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/install-remmina-in-ubuntu-desktop.png" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"><p> Remmina is an <strong>open-source desktop client written in GTK</strong> that lets you connect to remote computers.</p><p> It is a simpler alternative to tools like <strong>AnyDesk</strong> and <strong>TeamViewer</strong> . You can connect through various protocols like <strong>RDP, VNC, SSH, X2GO, HTTP(S)</strong> , and more. The feature-set can be extended with the help of available plugins if you need.</p><p> Note that Remmina is only available for Linux users. So, if you have a Linux machine and want to connect to any other remote system, Remmina is perfect.</p><p> I should also mention that it is one of the <a href="https://itsfoss.com/remote-desktop-tools/" rel="noreferrer">best remote desktop tools for Linux</a> .</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/remote-desktop-tools/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">9 Best Remote Desktop Tools for Linux</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Here, we list the best remote desktop tools for Linux along with their pros and cons.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Ankush Das</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/05/list-of-remote-desktop-tools.png" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"></div></a></figure><p> Now that you know about <a href="https://www.remmina.org/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Remmina</a> as a capable remote desktop tool. How do you use it?</p><p> Let me tell you more about it:</p><h2 id="get-started-by-installing-remmina-on-ubuntu"> Get Started by Installing Remmina on Ubuntu </h2><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remina-remote-linux-desktop-connected-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="754" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remina-remote-linux-desktop-connected-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/remina-remote-linux-desktop-connected-1.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remina-remote-linux-desktop-connected-1.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Remmina comes pre-installed in many Linux distributions, including the latest releases of Ubuntu and Fedora.</p><p> In either case, you can find it available in the official repositories for most Linux distributions.</p><p> If you want to install the latest version, I recommend installing the Flatpak or the Snap package.</p><p> For this article, I installed the <a href="https://snapcraft.io/remmina?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Snap package</a> from the Ubuntu&#39;s Software Center. You can choose to get the Flatpak package from <a href="https://flathub.org/apps/org.remmina.Remmina?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Flathub</a> as well.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> The entire setup is tested on and written for systems on the same subnetwork. In simpler terms, your devices should be connected to the same router.</div></div><h2 id="using-remmina-to-connect-to-a-linux-remote-machine-ubuntu"> Using Remmina to Connect to a Linux Remote Machine (Ubuntu)</h2><p> To test this use-case, I tried connecting to my Linux laptop from my Linux desktop computer.</p><p> Before connecting, you need to know the IP address of the remote system. In my case, I went to system settings and utilized the graphical user interface <strong>Wi-Fi→ Connection settings</strong> ( <em>gear icon next to the network connected</em> ) to check the IP address. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ip-address-settings-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="632" height="631" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/ip-address-settings-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ip-address-settings-1.png 632w"></figure><p> You can also use the terminal and type in the following to get the IP address:</p><pre> <code>ip a</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/find-ip-adress-terminal-1-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="786" height="533" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/find-ip-adress-terminal-1-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/find-ip-adress-terminal-1-1.png 786w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You might have more things listed here, but the IP address right to &quot;inet&quot; under an Ethernet connection (you can spot that by the text field link/ether) is what we need.</p><p> In my case, the IP address is <strong>192.168.1.14</strong></p><p> Next, you need two more things before you can connect to the remote machine:</p><ul><li> Enable remote desktop in the remote system you wish to connect.</li><li> The <strong>username</strong> and the <strong>password</strong> for remote connection.</li></ul><h3 id="enable-remote-connection-on-the-remote-system"> Enable remote connection on the remote system</h3><p> To get that, navigate through <strong>Settings → Sharing → Remote Desktop</strong> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1105" height="706" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-1.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-1.png 1105w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Here, you need to toggle (enable) <strong>Remote Desktop</strong> , check &quot; <strong>Enable Legacy VNC Protocol</strong> &quot;, and then <strong>Remote Control</strong> as shown in the screenshot below. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-options-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="752" height="849" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-options-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-enable-options-1.png 752w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> We utilize the <strong>Virtual Network Computing</strong> (VNC) protocol to connect, which is the preferred way to connect to Linux computers for most.</p><p> As you can notice, you can find the username and the password under the &quot; <strong>Authentication</strong> &quot; section in the image above.</p><p> Once you have the IP, authentication details, and enabled remote sharing, you just need to <strong>add a new connection profile</strong> and fill up the details. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-main-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="661" height="499" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-main-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-main-1.png 661w"></figure><p> Here&#39;s how that looks like: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-connection-vnc-protocol-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="893" height="663" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-connection-vnc-protocol-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-connection-vnc-protocol-1.png 893w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You can give it any name, and create a Group (if you need). For instance, I can have a group of home devices from a workplace, and keep it organized separately to identify remote computers easily.</p><p> For the protocol, use &quot; <strong>Remmina VNC Plugin</strong> &quot;.</p><p> The rest of the settings remain default, and ensure that the Quality is set to <strong>good</strong> . So, you can have a good user experience without requiring a superfast internet connection.</p><p> However, you can choose to change it if you think you have poor network connectivity.</p><p> Once you are done with setting the options, hit &quot; <strong>Save and Connect</strong> &quot;.</p><p> Of course, if you want to connect to a machine once from a guest computer, and do not want to save the details, you can avoid saving and hit &quot; <strong>Connect</strong> &quot;. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-incoming-desktop-connection-request-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="886" height="331" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-incoming-desktop-connection-request-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-incoming-desktop-connection-request-1.png 886w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You might be prompted for the connection for the first time. If you do not want this, you can change the authentication technique to &quot; <strong>Require a password</strong> &quot; in the remote desktop settings: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-control-access-methods-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="647" height="294" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remote-control-access-methods-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-control-access-methods-1.png 647w"></figure><p> And, voilà! You are now connected to the remote system. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-screenshot-linux-computer.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1188" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remote-desktop-screenshot-linux-computer.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/remote-desktop-screenshot-linux-computer.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/10/remote-desktop-screenshot-linux-computer.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remote-desktop-screenshot-linux-computer.png 2041w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> You should change the quality settings before connecting to a remote system to avoid crashes.</div></div><p> While you are connected to the remote machine, you can take a screenshot, scale the window size, duplicate the connection, and do several more useful things from the left sidebar.</p><p> Now, let us move on to a Windows system.</p><h2 id="using-remmina-to-connect-to-a-windows-remote-system"> Using Remmina to Connect to a Windows Remote System</h2><p> Just like a Linux (Ubuntu in our example) system, you have to enable remote desktop sharing before trying to connect to a Windows computer.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-green"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 💡</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> For Windows, you can only find the Remote Desktop option in the <b><strong style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Pro editions</strong></b> .<br><br> So, if you have Windows 10/11 Home edition, you cannot enable Remote Desktop unless you upgrade it to the professional edition.</div></div><p> Considering you have a license to Windows pro edition on your remote system.</p><p> Here&#39;s how to enable Remote Desktop sharing:</p><ol><li> Head to <strong>Settings → System → Remote Desktop</strong> . Now, enable the option as shown below: </li></ol><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/windows-enable-remote-desktop.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1424" height="942" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/windows-enable-remote-desktop.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/windows-enable-remote-desktop.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/windows-enable-remote-desktop.jpg 1424w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You will get a prompt to confirm the action. Proceed with it. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/prompt-enable-remote-desktop-windows.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1055" height="385" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/prompt-enable-remote-desktop-windows.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/prompt-enable-remote-desktop-windows.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/prompt-enable-remote-desktop-windows.jpg 1055w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><ol start="2"><li> Next, we need information to connect to this Windows device. For that, you need to your network settings, and hit &quot; <strong>Properties</strong> &quot; to get network information (IP address).<br><br> In this case, we have a wired connection. </li></ol><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/network-properties-windows.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1422" height="935" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/network-properties-windows.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/network-properties-windows.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/network-properties-windows.jpg 1422w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> On the next screen, you will have the IP address of your system as shown below: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/windows-ip-address.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="756" height="590" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/windows-ip-address.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/windows-ip-address.jpg 756w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> In case you have a wireless connection, you will have to navigate to &quot; <strong>Change adapter options</strong> &quot; in the network status screen and then right-click on the <strong>Wi-Fi adapter</strong> connected to your computer.</p><p> Now, check the status of the Wi-Fi network and click on &quot; <strong>Details</strong> &quot; to get the IP address, as shown in the screenshots below: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-gallery-card kg-width-wide kg-card-hascaption"><div class="kg-gallery-container"><div class="kg-gallery-row"><div class="kg-gallery-image"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/wifi-status-windows-1.jpg" width="545" height="398" loading="lazy" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"></div><div class="kg-gallery-image"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/wifi-status-details-1.jpg" width="456" height="582" loading="lazy" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"></div><div class="kg-gallery-image"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/network-connection-details-wifi-1-1.jpg" width="502" height="574" loading="lazy" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu"></div></div></div><figcaption><p> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Checking Wi-Fi network details on Windows</span></p></figcaption></figure><p> For the tutorial, I used the wired connection. So, the IP address for me remains:</p><p> <strong>192.168.1.3</strong></p><p> I created a new remote connection profile with the above IP address and its protocol as <strong>RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol)</strong> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/list-of-devices-connected-remmina-1-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="767" height="522" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/list-of-devices-connected-remmina-1-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/list-of-devices-connected-remmina-1-1.png 767w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-connect-windows-computer-rdp-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="862" height="689" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-connect-windows-computer-rdp-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-connect-windows-computer-rdp-1.png 862w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> The username and password are the same as your Windows computer credentials.</p><p> For me, it was my Microsoft account credentials linked to my Windows system. If you do not have a Microsoft account linked, it will be your local username and password.</p><p> Of course, you can choose to add a new user just for remote desktop if you like.</p><p> Considering I accidentally entered the local credentials instead of my microsoft@outlook.com details, it prompted me again for authentication. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-authentication-microsoft-account-1-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="887" height="569" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-authentication-microsoft-account-1-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-authentication-microsoft-account-1-1.png 887w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Once you are done authenticating, you will get another prompt asking you to verify the certificate where your desktop name will also show up as follows: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-accept-certificate-windows-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="887" height="569" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-accept-certificate-windows-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-accept-certificate-windows-1.png 887w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Accept the certificate. If you are incredibly cautious about the connection, you can pick to view the installed certificates on your system and verify by following <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/wcf/feature-details/how-to-view-certificates-with-the-mmc-snap-in?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Microsoft&#39;s documentation</a> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-remote-desktop-windows.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="1720" height="1026" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/remmina-remote-desktop-windows.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/remmina-remote-desktop-windows.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1600/2023/10/remmina-remote-desktop-windows.png 1600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/remmina-remote-desktop-windows.png 1720w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> And, that is it! You are connected to the Windows remote machine.</p><p> <strong>One important bit here</strong> : you should <strong>enable the dynamic resolution update</strong> from the sidebar to make the resolution adapt to your screen size. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/dynamic-resolution.png" class="kg-image" alt="Install, Configure and Use Remmina on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="480" height="291"></figure><p> For the tutorial, I have tested a Linux remote machine and a Windows system, which are the two most popular use-cases.</p><p> You need a static IP and IP forwarding to test the SSH connection protocol.</p><p> For the rest of the options in the sidebar, you get re-sizing the window, taking a screenshot of the remote machine, duplicating a connection, tweaking the connection quality for slow/fast performance, and more.</p><h2 id="wrapping-up"> Wrapping Up</h2><p> Remmina works well for simple remote desktop connection, with advanced abilities for users who require it.</p><p> You can customize your remote connection with advanced options and SSH connection. However, if you do not know what you are doing, you probably do not need those options.</p><p> <em>How else do you use the Remmina app for remote connections? Let me know in the comments below.</em></p> ; 
How to Install the Latest LibreOffice on UbuntuWant the latest and greatest of LibreOffice on Ubuntu? Here's an easy method for you. https://itsfoss.com/install-libreoffice-ubuntu/ 64fc1dd4bb002c95983060d2 Installation 📥UbuntuAbhishek Prakash Mon, 23 Oct 2023 05:52:24 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/latest-libreoffice-ubuntu.png" alt="How to Install the Latest LibreOffice on Ubuntu"><p> LibreOffice comes preinstalled in Ubuntu.</p><p> However, if you opted for the minimal Ubuntu install, removed it for some other office suite, you can easily install it using this command:</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install libreoffice</code></pre><p> That&#39;s fine. But the LibreOffice version provided by the Ubuntu repository may not be the latest one.</p><p> If you are hearing about a new LibreOffice version release, most likely, you won&#39;t be getting the new release. That&#39;s because Ubuntu keeps it on a stable release.</p><p> And that&#39;s fine for most users. However, if you are not &#39;among most users&#39; and you like to get the latest LibreOffice in Ubuntu, you can totally do that.</p><p> There are two ways to do that:</p><ul><li> Use official PPA (recommended)</li><li> Download deb file from LibreOffice</li></ul><p> Let&#39;s see them one by one.</p><h2 id="method-1-install-latest-libreoffice-via-official-ppa-recommended"> Method 1: Install latest LibreOffice via official PPA (recommended)</h2><p> You can use the official “LibreOffice Fresh” PPA to install the latest stable release of LibreOffice on Ubuntu based distributions.</p><p> The PPA provides the latest stable release of the LibreOffice, not a development release. So, this makes it the ideal choice to get the newer LibreOffice version on Ubuntu.</p><p> You don&#39;t even need to uninstall the previous version using this method. It will update the existing LibreOffice to the newer version.</p><pre> <code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:libreoffice/ppa sudo apt update sudo apt install libreoffice</code></pre><p> Since you are adding a PPA, you&#39;ll also get updates on the newer version installed this way.</p><h2 id="method-2-get-the-binaries-from-the-website-if-you-want"> Method 2: Get the binaries from the website (if you want)</h2><p> You can always go to the <a href="https://www.libreoffice.org/download/download-libreoffice?ref=itsfoss.com">download section of the LibreOfiice website</a> and download the deb file of the latest version. You&#39;ll also see the option to download an older but LTS stable version. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/download-libreoffice.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Install the Latest LibreOffice on Ubuntu" loading="lazy" width="824" height="799" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/download-libreoffice.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/download-libreoffice.png 824w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> I believe you already <a href="https://itsfoss.com/install-deb-files-ubuntu/">know how to install applications from a deb file</a> . Right click on the deb file, select to open it with Software Center. Once in software center, you can click the install button to install it.</p><h2 id="conclusion">结论</h2><p>The downside of the second method is that if there is an update, you&#39;ll have to download the deb file again, remove the previous LibreOffice version and install the new version with the newly downloaded deb file.</p><p> In contrast, the PPA gives you update automatically with the system updates. That&#39;s the reason why I recommend the PPA, specially when it is maintained by the LibreOffice team itself.</p><p> By the way, here are some <a href="https://itsfoss.com/libreoffice-tips/">tips on getting more out of LibreOffice</a> :</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/libreoffice-tips/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">15 LibreOffice Tips to Get More Out of it</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">LibreOffice is an excellent office suite. These LibreOffice tips will enable you to use it more effectively.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="How to Install the Latest LibreOffice on Ubuntu"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Abhishek Prakash</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/wordpress/2017/12/LibreOffice-logo.jpeg" alt="How to Install the Latest LibreOffice on Ubuntu"></div></a></figure><p> I hope this quick tip helped you get the latest LibreOffice on Ubuntu-based distributions. Let me know if you have questions.</p> ; 
Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password ManagersWhat is your favorite open-source password manager? https://itsfoss.com/bitwarden-vs-proton-pass/ 6533585b8ebe181c27ab5422 ComparisonAnkush Das Sat, 21 Oct 2023 11:16:29 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/biwarden-vs-protonpass-ft.png" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers"><p> Bitwarden and Proton Pass are two excellent open-source password managers.</p><p> While Bitwarden has established itself as a solid option for more than six years now, Proton Pass is a newer entry.</p><p> What should you pick? <strong>An existing trustworthy password manager or a newer option built by Proton</strong> , known for its privacy-focused products.</p><p> I have been using Bitwarden, and Proton Pass with their premium features. Primarily I utilize Bitwarden, but I have been experimenting with Proton Pass since its launch.</p><p> So, here, I shall share my user experience insights and other pointers that you need to know when selecting one as your password manager.</p><h2 id="use-case-and-app-availability"> Use-Case and App Availability</h2><p> When it comes to a password manager, the app availability and your use-case play an important role.</p><p> You have to ask yourself questions like:</p><ul><li> <strong>Where do I need the password manager? (Desktop/Mobile/Web Browser)</strong></li><li> <strong>What are the extra features that it offers?</strong></li><li> <strong>Do I stick to a single service for multiple utilities?</strong></li></ul><p> I shall highlight the features in the later part of this article.</p><p> But before that, you need to decide where you want to use the password manager and if you would like to keep the password manager service separate.</p><p> Proton Pass is only available as a <strong>browser extension</strong> and for <strong>mobile platforms</strong> (at the time of writing). </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1569" height="739" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/proton-pass.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/proton-pass.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass.jpg 1569w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You can get the extension for <strong>Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Brave, Edge</strong> , and other Chrome-based web browsers. Additionally, you can choose to install it on your <strong>Android or iOS</strong> device. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-1.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="822" height="602" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-1.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-1.jpg 822w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> ✅ <em>If you do not need a desktop app for your password manager and want to continue using all the services by Proton, Proton Pass is a suitable choice.</em></p><p> On the contrary, Bitwarden is available for <strong>Windows, macOS, and Linux</strong> as a <strong>desktop app</strong> .</p><p> In addition, you can get the add-on for <strong>Google Chrome, Firefox, Vivaldi, Opera, Edge, Tor, and DuckDuckGo for Mac</strong> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-ui.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="820" height="853" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-ui.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-ui.jpg 820w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> For mobile platforms, it is available for iPhone, Apple Watch, and Android phones. You can also install it from F-Droid for Android.</p><p> Not just limited to all these, you can use it as a <strong>web app</strong> or<strong> </strong>through <strong>a command-line interface</strong> .</p><p> ✅ <em>Bitwarden should be the perfect pick if you require the password manager available across multiple platforms without any compromise.</em></p><h2 id="user-experience"> User Experience</h2><p> Bitwarden&#39;s user experience can be described as straightforward and non-intrusive.</p><p> You can see how the browser add-on looks like: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-firefox.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="817" height="819" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-firefox.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-extension-firefox.jpg 817w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Sure, the user interface has improved over the years, but it always sticks to its roots, ie, <strong>simplicity over a beautified UI</strong> .</p><p> It does not get in your way and provides a familiar user experience at all times. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-login.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="800" height="818" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-login.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-login.jpg 800w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You can tweak the theme among dark, light, solarized and nord presets. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-theme.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="766" height="507" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-theme.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-theme.jpg 766w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Whether you are on the desktop app, mobile app or the browser extension, you get the same convenience.</p><p> Proton Pass <strong>stands out with its layout</strong> , and provides an expanded overlook at your credentials every time you access the extension. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-2.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="809" height="598" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-2.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-ui-2.jpg 809w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Some users could prefer <strong>the modern approach to the UI</strong> . So, it is up to your personal preferences.</p><p> I like Bitwarden&#39;s traditional approach.</p><h2 id="pricing"> Pricing</h2><p> You can get started using both the services for free.</p><p> Bitwarden and Proton Pass can be used to store unlimited logins with no restrictions to the number of devices on its free plan.</p><p> If you need features like emergency access, family access, secure storage, 2FA authenticator, and hide-my-email aliases, you need a premium subscription. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-pricing.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1078" height="563" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-pricing.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/bitwarden-pricing.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-pricing.jpg 1078w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> <a href="https://bitwarden.com/pricing/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Bitwarden</a> starts just at <strong>10 USD</strong> per year, with its family plan ( <em>six accounts</em> ) at <strong>40 USD</strong> per year. <strong>Incredibly affordable</strong> for the masses.</p><p> <a href="https://account.proton.me/pass/signup?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Proton Pass</a> is on the expensive side at <strong>47.88 Euro per year</strong> for its plus plan. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/protonpass-pricing.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="954" height="475" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/protonpass-pricing.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/protonpass-pricing.jpg 954w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> However, if you utilize all other Proton services, and opt for a Proton Unlimited subscription, you can get premium perks for <strong>Proton Pass, Mail, VPN, Drive, and Calendar</strong> .</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card kg-card-hascaption"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://proton.go2cloud.org/aff_c?offer_id=15&amp;aff_id=1173&amp;ref=itsfoss.com"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Proton Mail: Get a private, secure, and encrypted email account | Proton</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Proton Mail is the world&#39;s largest secure email service with over 100 million users. Available on Web, iOS, Android, and desktop. Protected by Swiss privacy law.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://proton.go2cloud.org/favicons/apple-touch-icon.png" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">Proton</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://proton.me/images/social/proton-mail-og.png" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers"></div></a><figcaption><p> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">(Affiliate Link)</span></p></figcaption></figure><h2 id="features"> Features</h2><p> Both the password managers are quite competent. So, you can expect the essentials with each of them.</p><p> Here are the things that are common between them:</p><ul><li> <strong>Password generator</strong></li><li> <strong>Secure notes</strong></li><li> <strong>Autofill</strong></li><li> <strong>Card and login credentials</strong></li><li> <strong>Mobile apps for convenient access to credentials</strong></li></ul><p> Now let me highlight the things that make each of the services stand out as per my experience:</p><h3 id="bitwarden"> Bitwarden</h3><p> One of the key offerings of Bitwarden is its &quot; <strong>Send</strong> &quot; feature. You can send a file (up to 500 MB) or a piece of text/note to anyone via a secure link, which keeps things end-to-end encrypted. This option is accessible on <strong>desktop app, extension, and the web vault</strong> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-send-web-vault.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1402" height="1134" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-send-web-vault.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/bitwarden-send-web-vault.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-send-web-vault.jpg 1402w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You can keep the link protected by adding a passphrase known only to the receiver. More customization options are also available, like setting an expiry timer to it or the ability to destroy the link once the file has been downloaded.</p><p> I would not call it as a way to securely send files. But it is more suitable to send private documents (similar to email attachments) and text files.</p><p> Next, Bitwarden offers a <strong>family plan</strong> where you can share a <strong>single subscription with six accounts</strong> . There&#39;s no such offering with Proton Pass.</p><p> Another important feature that I&#39;d like to emphasize: <strong>emergency access</strong> .</p><p> With every credential going into the password manager, it is the one place where <strong>all your access secrets lie</strong> . To make it convenient for a trusted friend or family member to access your passwords when something happens to you, you can set up emergency access. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/emergency-access-bitwarden.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1261" height="632" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/emergency-access-bitwarden.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/emergency-access-bitwarden.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/emergency-access-bitwarden.jpg 1261w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Of course, before giving the authorized user access to your account, you can choose to set a duration to be able to confirm or deny it. If you take no action, the access will be granted to your trusted user. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-emergency-invite.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1025" height="672" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/bitwarden-emergency-invite.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/bitwarden-emergency-invite.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-emergency-invite.jpg 1025w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> You can access the emergency contact option only on the <a href="https://vault.bitwarden.com/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer"><b><strong style="white-space: pre-wrap;">web vault</strong></b></a> <b><strong style="white-space: pre-wrap;">.</strong></b></div></div><p> <strong>Not to forget:</strong> the password generator includes history for both the services. Bitwarden <strong>retains history for a longer time</strong> , but Proton Pass keeps only one day of history. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/bitwarden-password-generator.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="467" height="751"></figure><p> Other feature differences include:</p><ul><li> <strong>Ability to export in .CSV</strong></li><li> <strong>Ability to tweak the autofill behavior</strong></li><li> <strong>Access to web vault</strong></li><li> <strong>Desktop apps</strong></li><li> <strong>Identity info</strong></li><li> <strong>Ability to self-host on your server</strong></li></ul><p> I have never had any significant issues with Bitwarden for all the features listed.</p><p> Of course, if you decide to self-host it, you need to ensure that you have the technical expertise and the time to maintain it. Refer to its <a href="https://bitwarden.com/help/self-host-an-organization/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">official documentation</a> to explore more about deploying Bitwarden yourself.</p><p> <strong>The only problem I noticed</strong> : sometimes on my Android phone, the autofill does not show up along the keyboard app as a suggestion. Of course, this depends on the customized Android experience provided by various smartphone manufacturers. So, it may or may not be a Bitwarden-specific issue.</p><p> <strong>Suggested Read</strong> 📖</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/password-managers-linux/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Top 5 Best Password Managers for Linux [2023]</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Linux Password Managers to the rescue!</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Ankush Das</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/best-password-managers-for-linux.png" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers"></div></a></figure><h3 id="proton-pass"> Proton Pass</h3><p> If we compare both in terms of &quot;number of features&quot;, Bitwarden gets the edge.</p><p> However, Proton Pass ticks all the essentials you need in a password manager and goes beyond as a privacy-focused tool. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-password-generator.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="401" height="533"></figure><p> Proton Pass supports generating email aliases, all thanks to having <a href="https://simplelogin.io/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">SimpleLogin</a> &#39;s expertise.</p><p> If you are curious: SimpleLogin is one of the most popular <a href="https://itsfoss.com/protect-email-address/" rel="noreferrer">tools to protect your email address</a> .</p><p> So, with that being integrated with Proton Pass service, it gets <strong>convenient to quickly create an email alias</strong> , and save the login at the same time. The email you signed up with for Proton Pass will be the real email address.</p><p> I wish if they provided an option to set new target email addresses, this would make the extra premium for Proton Pass worth it.</p><p> Additionally, if you are someone who utilizes some or all Proton services, it should be a good user experience with Proton Pass. You do not have to switch or sign up for a different platform.</p><p> With Proton Pass, you also get the essentials to <strong>import/export, control certain security measures, and tweak the password manager&#39;s behavior</strong> . </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-settings.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Bitwarden vs. Proton Pass: Comparing Top Open-Source Password Managers" loading="lazy" width="1103" height="998" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/proton-pass-settings.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/proton-pass-settings.jpg 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/proton-pass-settings.jpg 1103w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> So, Proton Pass can be an all-in-one solution for Proton users.</p><p> And, yes, Proton Pass hasn&#39;t been around for a long time now for me to notice any issues with its mobile app. So far, so good.</p><h2 id="what-should-you-pick"> What Should You Pick?</h2><p> Considering you know what&#39;s common between them, it comes to your personal user experience taste, budget (if opting for premium), and the feature-set.</p><p> For my use-case, I do not see Proton Pass replacing Bitwarden anytime soon.</p><p> However, if I decide to take a Proton Unlimited subscription or get involved with Proton&#39;s offerings more than ever, I might ditch Bitwarden.</p><p> <em>💬 What do you think? Do you think Proton Pass is worth the extra premium, or better with Proton&#39;s bundled subscription? Is Bitwarden your favorite? Share your thoughts in the comments down below.</em></p> ; 
